Second Regular Session of the 124th General Assembly (2026)
PRINTING CODE. Amendments: Whenever an existing statute (or a section of the Indiana
Constitution) is being amended, the text of the existing provision will appear in this style type,
additions will appear in this style type, and deletions will appear in this style type.
Additions: Whenever a new statutory provision is being enacted (or a new constitutional
provision adopted), the text of the new provision will appear in this style type. Also, the
word NEW will appear in that style type in the introductory clause of each SECTION that adds
a new provision to the Indiana Code or the Indiana Constitution.
Conflict reconciliation: Text in a statute in this style type or this style type reconciles conflicts
between statutes enacted by the 2025 Regular Session of the General Assembly.
ENGROSSED
SENATE BILL No. 200
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
education.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 20-26-5-4.1 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
3 1, 2026]: Sec. 4.1. (a) This section applies to a vendor contract
4 entered into, amended, or renewed after June 30, 2026.
5 (b) As used in this section, "automatic renewal provision"
6 means a provision in a vendor contract that provides for the
7 automatic renewal of the contract unless the governing body of a
8 school corporation or the equivalent authority for a charter school
9 gives notice to the vendor that the school corporation or charter
10 school intends to terminate the vendor contract at the end of the
11 contract term.
12 (c) As used in this section, "choice of law provision" means a
13 term within a vendor contract that subjects the vendor contract to
14 the laws of a state other than Indiana.
15 (d) As used in this section, "indemnity provision" means a
16 provision, a clause, a covenant, or an agreement that:
17 (1) is contained in, collateral to, or affecting a vendor
ES 200—LS 6948/DI 152

2
1 contract; and
2 (2) purports to indemnify, defend, or hold harmless, or has the
3 effect of indemnifying, defending, or holding harmless, a
4 vendor against liability for loss or damage resulting from:
5 (A) negligence;
6 (B) intentional acts; or
7 (C) omissions;
8 of the vendor or an agent, employee, servant, or independent
9 contractor that is directly responsible to the vendor.
10 (e) As used in this section, "vendor contract" means a contract
11 between a governing body of a school corporation or the equivalent
12 authority for a charter school and a vendor in which the vendor
13 promises to provide goods or services.
14 (f) Notwithstanding any other law, an indemnity provision in a
15 vendor contract under this section is:
16 (1) against public policy; and
17 (2) void and unenforceable.
18 (g) Notwithstanding any other law, a choice of law provision in
19 a vendor contract under this section is:
20 (1) against public policy; and
21 (2) void and unenforceable.
22 A vendor contract is only subject to the laws of the state of Indiana.
23 (h) Notwithstanding any other law, an automatic renewal
24 provision in a vendor contract under this section is:
25 (1) against public policy; and
26 (2) void and unenforceable.
27 SECTION 2. IC 20-26-5-48 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
28 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
29 1, 2026]: Sec. 48. If a public school, including a charter school,
30 allows a postsecondary educational institution to provide
31 information regarding postsecondary education or training to
32 students of the public school, the public school shall allow military
33 personnel to provide, in the same manner as the postsecondary
34 educational institution, information regarding educational
35 opportunities and financial education benefits available for service
36 in the armed forces, national guard, or reserve component of the
37 armed forces or national guard.
38 SECTION 3. IC 20-26-20-4, AS ADDED BY P.L.86-2020,
39 SECTION 5, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
40 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 4. (a) Upon request by an organization under
41 section 3 of this chapter, a public school shall provide at least one (1)
42 time each school year, a day and time, which may be during the school
ES 200—LS 6948/DI 152

3
1 day or at a time where a majority of students and their families will
2 be present on school property, as approved by the public school, for
3 the representatives of the organization to provide information to
4 students on school property as described in section 3 of this chapter.
5 (b) An organization may submit a grievance to the department,
6 in a manner prescribed by the department, if a public school
7 refuses to allow an organization to provide information to students
8 on school property as required by subsection (a).
